{"cursor":"3394","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Sir Arthur John Wilton' KCMG KCVO MC (21 October 1921 â 12 June 2011), known as\n'John Wilton', was a British diplomat who was Ambassador to Kuwait (1970â1974)\nand to Saudi Arabia (1976â1979).\n\nWilton was born on 21 October 1921, the son of Walter and Annetta Wilton. He\nwas educated at Wanstead High School, winning an Open Scholarship to St\nJohn's College, Oxford in 1940. In 1942 he was commissioned into the Royal\nUlster Rifles, and served with the Irish Brigade in North Africa, Italy and\nAustria between 1943 and 1946. He was awarded the Military Cross and was\nMentioned in Despatches. He was awarded a War-time MA (first class Honours)\nfrom the University of Oxford on the basis of the time spent at Oxford and on\nwar service.\n\nHe entered HM Diplomatic Service in 1947, with postings in Lebanon, Egypt, Gulf\nShaikdoms (including the post of the first Political Officer resident in Doha,\nQatar, August 1949 â July 1950), Yugoslavia and Roumania. He was Director of the\nMiddle East Centre for Arab Studies in Lebanon from 1960 to 1965, Deputy High\nCommissioner in Aden 1966â1967, Ambassador to Kuwait 1970â1974, Assistant Under-\nSecretary of State, Foreign and Commonwealth Office 1974â1976, and Ambassador to\nSaudi Arabia 1976â1979. He was also Director of the London House for Overseas\nGraduates 1979â1986 and Chairman of the Arab-British Centre 1981â1986.\n\nAfter he retired to Devon, he was President of the Plymouth branch of the\nEnglish Speaking Union (from 1991) and a Trustee of the Arab-British Chamber\nCharitable Foundation (from 1989), churchwarden of St. Mauriceâs Church,\nPlympton, Devon and chairman of the charity Call South West. He was awarded an\nHonorary LLD in 1986 by New England College, New Hampshire, USA.\n\nWilton died suddenly on 12 June 2011, aged 89. He is survived by his wife of 60\nyears Maureen, children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren.\n